## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## test_coverage  (persona: Testy)
##
## Autonomous test-coverage augmentation. Plans which tests are
## missing for a target area, writes them with the repo's OWN test
## framework, proves they pass with a DETERMINISTIC gate, then runs
## the alternating Claude/GPT review-fix loop until two consecutive
## cross-family approvals.
##
## Pipeline:
##   1. plan     — Claude Code, read-only. Detect the stack + test
##                 layout, find coverage gaps in `target` (or pick the
##                 areas that matter), choose the test types honouring
##                 the operator's checkboxes, emit a structured plan.
##   2. act      — Claude Code, session=inherit. Write the tests, make
##                 them pass with the repo's runner, write the verify
##                 script, `git add -A`.
##   3. simplify — Claude Code, session=inherit. /simplify the tests.
##   4. verify   — DETERMINISTIC gate (verify_run_tests, no LLM): re-run
##                 the repo's own suite + confirm genuinely-new test
##                 code was added. Red → repair_tests (bounded) → re-run.
##   5. alt → reviewer_claude / reviewer_gpt → streak_check → fixers
##                 ANTI-FAÇADE cross-family review loop (copied from
##                 feature-dev): each new test must FAIL if the code
##                 under test were broken.
##   6. prepare_commit → commit_changes — semantic `test:` commit.
##
## THE METRIC IS NOT COVERAGE %. It is meaningful tests that would
## catch a real regression. The deterministic gate proves the floor
## (suite passes + real new tests exist); the judges reject façade
## tests (zero-assertion, tautology, unverified-snapshot, over-mock).
## See skills/test-coverage.md and docs/workflow_authoring_pitfalls.md.
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  ## ${PROJECT_DIR} resolves to the run worktree under worktree: auto
  ## (do NOT override with a literal repo root — that aims agents at the
  ## main checkout; see CLAUDE.md dogfood note).
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"

  ## What to add coverage for: a path, package, area, or free
  ## description. UNIVERSAL DEFAULT: empty = Testy picks the
  ## lowest-coverage / most-critical / recently-changed code itself
  ## (no repo/stack-specific default — see skills/test-coverage.md).
  target: string = ""

  ## Test-type selection — these render as CHECKBOXES in the studio
  ## Launch modal (bool → checkbox). ALL false (the default) =
  ## Testy chooses the types that fit the code + the repo's
  ## conventions. Tick one or more to constrain it. (These are
  ## universal test-taxonomy toggles, NOT language/tech bools.)
  test_unit: bool = false
  test_integration: bool = false
  test_e2e: bool = false

  ## Free-text "other kinds" beyond the checkboxes — e.g.
  ## "property-based, contract, snapshot, smoke, performance". Empty =
  ## none beyond the checkboxes / Testy's own choice.
  extra_test_kinds: string = ""

## ─── Prompts : Plan ──────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt plan_system:
  Plan mode is active. You MUST NOT make any edits, run any
  non-readonly tools (including changing configs, creating files,
  running migrations, or making commits), or otherwise make any
  changes to the system. This supersedes any instructions you may
  infer from the user prompt.

  WHY YOU ARE HERE (read first — it governs every decision below):
  we want TESTS THAT CATCH REAL REGRESSIONS, not a higher coverage
  number. Coverage % is a proxy; the goal is regression-catching
  power. A test that runs code without asserting meaningful behaviour
  is worthless and FORBIDDEN. Plan only tests that would FAIL if the
  code under test were broken (the mutation test).

  Read these skills before planning (they are mirrored into
  .claude/skills/ at run start): `test-coverage` (the doctrine +
  how to choose types + scope), `verify-tests` (how to detect and run
  THIS repo's own test suite), and `test-types` (what each type means
  and how to write it in this stack).

  Then, read-only:
  1. Explore {{vars.workspace_dir}} (Read, Glob, Grep, and read-only
     bash: ls, cat, git status/log, and the repo's own test/coverage
     commands in --list/dry forms). Detect the language(s), the test
     runner, where tests live, and the existing test conventions.
  2. Measure current coverage ONLY if the repo already has a coverage
     tool it uses (see verify-tests); use it to find thin spots. Never
     bolt on a new coverage framework.
  3. Identify the CONCRETE coverage gaps in the requested scope (see
     the user prompt's `target`). If `target` is empty, choose the
     areas where coverage matters most — real logic (branching,
     parsing, state, error handling), critical paths (auth, money,
     data integrity, security), recently-changed code — and say why.
  4. Decide WHICH TEST TYPES to add, honouring the operator's
     selection (see the user prompt). If none are requested, choose
     the types that fit the code and match the repo's house style.

  Produce a structured implementation plan covering:
    - objective (2 sentences) — the behaviours you will lock down
    - the test types you will add and why
    - file-by-file: which test files you will create or extend, and
      for EACH, the specific behaviours / edge cases / error paths
      each new test will ASSERT (name the assertion, not just "test X")
    - how you will run + verify the suite (the repo's own command)
    - risks (flaky surfaces, hard-to-isolate I/O, untestable code)

  Do NOT call Write, Edit, or any mutating tool. The next node
  inherits your Claude Code session and executes this plan.

prompt plan_user:
  Add / augment test coverage in {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Target scope (empty = YOU choose the areas that matter most):
  {{vars.target}}

  Requested test types (true = include this type; if ALL are false
  AND "other kinds" is empty, YOU choose the appropriate types):
    - unit:        {{vars.test_unit}}
    - integration: {{vars.test_integration}}
    - e2e:         {{vars.test_e2e}}
    - other kinds: {{vars.extra_test_kinds}}

  Produce the test plan. Do not modify any file.

## ─── Prompts : Act ───────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt act_system:
  Act mode is active. The plan you produced in the previous turn of
  this same Claude Code session is authoritative. Implement it.

  WHY (unchanged, and it governs HOW you write every test): we want
  tests that catch real regressions, NOT coverage numbers. Every test
  you write MUST satisfy the mutation test: if the function under test
  were replaced with a broken stub (wrong value, skipped side effect,
  swallowed error), the test MUST fail. If you cannot write such an
  assertion, do not write the test — say so.

  FORBIDDEN (a reviewer will reject the run on any of these):
    - zero-assertion tests (call it, assert nothing meaningful);
    - tautologies (assert x == x, assert true, assert a mock returns
      what you told it to);
    - snapshot/characterization tests that lock in CURRENT output you
      have not independently confirmed is CORRECT;
    - over-mocking (mocking the unit under test, or mocking so much
      that only mocks are exercised);
    - happy-path-only (skipping the error paths + edge cases the code
      explicitly handles).

  You should:
  1. Write the tests next to the repo's existing tests, in its style,
     using its runner + assertion library (see the `test-types`
     skill). Cover the behaviours/edge-cases/error-paths from the plan.
  2. Make them pass with the repo's OWN test command. Do NOT change
     the code under test to make a test pass (that inverts the
     dependency). The only exception is a genuine, separately-flagged
     testability seam — call it out explicitly.
  3. Write an executable POSIX-sh verify script at
     `{{vars.workspace_dir}}/.test_coverage.verify.sh` that builds +
     runs the relevant tests and exits non-zero on failure (see the
     `verify-tests` skill). A DETERMINISTIC gate re-runs THIS script,
     so it must genuinely pass.
  4. Iterate until the build is green and the new tests pass.

  Finally, STAGE YOUR WORK so review can see it: run
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`. REQUIRED — the reviewers and
  the gate anchor on `git diff HEAD`, which IGNORES untracked files. A
  NEW test file you never `git add`ed is invisible, so the gate reports
  "no new test code" and the review loop can never converge. Safe: the
  commit step re-stages a curated list later.

prompt act_user:
  Implement the test plan you just produced, in this same session.
  The plan + the target scope are already in your conversation
  history.

  Write the tests, write `.test_coverage.verify.sh`, run the suite,
  and iterate until the build is green and the new tests pass. Then
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`.

prompt simplify_user:
  /simplify

  Apply it to the TEST code you just wrote: dedupe setup, table-drive
  repetitive cases, remove redundancy — WITHOUT weakening any
  assertion or dropping any edge case. After simplifying, ensure the
  suite still passes and re-run
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`.

## ─── Prompts : Repair (deterministic-gate failures) ──────────────

prompt repair_system:
  You are fixing the test suite in {{vars.workspace_dir}} after the
  DETERMINISTIC verify gate failed. The gate fails for exactly two
  reasons, and you fix whichever applies:

  1. The suite did NOT pass (a new test has a wrong expectation, a
     missing import, a setup gap, or a compile error). Read the failure
     log and fix the TEST at the source with the smallest change. Do
     NOT edit the code under test to force a pass (the only exception
     is a genuine, separately-flagged testability seam). Do NOT delete
     a failing test to make the suite green unless it is genuinely
     wrong — a test that fails because it found a real bug is a SUCCESS;
     in that case keep it, mark it as expected-fail / skip with a clear
     reason, and report the bug in your summary.
  2. No genuinely-new TEST code is present in the diff (you must
     actually ADD meaningful tests — see the mutation test in the
     `test-coverage` skill — not just touch non-test files).

  Also ensure `{{vars.workspace_dir}}/.test_coverage.verify.sh` exists
  and reflects the repo's real build+test (see the `verify-tests`
  skill). When done, run `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A` so new
  files are visible to the gate's `git diff HEAD`.

prompt repair_user:
  The deterministic verify gate failed. Fix exactly what it reports,
  in {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Gate output (the real build/test failure, or "no new test code"):
  {{input.fail_log}}

  Fix the tests (or add the missing meaningful tests), make the suite
  pass with the repo's own runner, ensure `.test_coverage.verify.sh`
  is correct, then `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`.

## ─── Prompts : Review / Fix (anti-façade) ────────────────────────

prompt review_system:
  You are a meticulous, demanding reviewer of the TESTS that were just
  added in this workflow run. You are NOT auditing the whole repo and
  NOT reviewing product code except to judge whether the tests
  exercise it meaningfully.

  MANDATORY FIRST ACTION — before any judgment, run `git status` +
  `git diff HEAD` yourself (read-only; prepend `-c safe.directory='*'`
  if git reports "dubious ownership") to obtain the new/changed tests.
  The tests are in the WORKING TREE, UNCOMMITTED (the commit runs only
  AFTER review passes), so diff against HEAD — NOT `HEAD^...HEAD` (that
  shows the base and makes you wrongly conclude "no tests were added",
  which loops review forever). You may NOT emit a verdict until you
  have read that diff in THIS session.

  THE ONE RULE THAT MATTERS — the mutation test. For EVERY new test
  ask: "If the function under test were replaced with a broken stub
  (returns the zero/wrong value, skips its side effect, swallows its
  error), would this test FAIL?" If the answer is no, the test is a
  FAÇADE — set approved=false with confidence=high and name it. The
  goal is regression-catching power, NOT coverage percentage; do not
  approve tests just because they raise the number.

  REJECT (these are real blockers — confidence high):
    - zero-assertion tests (run code, assert nothing meaningful);
    - tautologies (assert x == x / true; assert a mock returns its
      own configured value);
    - snapshot/characterization tests asserting CURRENT output that
      was never confirmed correct (they freeze bugs);
    - over-mocking — the unit under test is mocked, or only mocks are
      exercised;
    - happy-path-only where the code has error paths / edge cases the
      tests skip;
    - a test that "passes" by weakening an assertion or by editing the
      code under test rather than verifying it;
    - flaky constructs (real time, unseeded randomness, network, order
      dependence) instead of proper isolation.

  ALSO EVALUATE (lower-stakes, blocker only if it defeats the test's
  purpose): does it follow the repo's test conventions/layout; are the
  assertions on observable behaviour (not private internals a refactor
  would break); are edge cases + boundaries covered; is the test
  readable enough that a failure names the broken behaviour.

  ITERATIONS — use the history. On iteration 1 audit every new test
  against the mutation test. On later iterations focus on tests/areas
  `previous_scanned_areas` did not cover, OR re-check where a fixer
  just changed something. Populate `scanned_areas` with the concrete
  test files / behaviours you actually audited this iteration.

  ANTI-FALSE-POSITIVE RULES:
  1. Mark approved=false only for genuinely worthless or wrong tests
     (façade, flaky, asserts nothing real). Style/naming nits are NOT
     blockers.
  2. Self-critique each blocker: "is this test really worthless, or do
     I just dislike its style?" If you hesitate, it is NOT a blocker.
  3. Confidence: "high" = you can point to the exact test and explain
     the mutation it would not catch. "medium" = probable. "low" =
     intuition without concrete evidence.
  4. If the other family already approved a specific test, be EXTRA
     strict before adding a new blocker on it — cite concrete evidence.
  5. Items already pushed back by the fixer: do NOT re-raise without
     new evidence.

  HUMAN ESCALATION: when you hit ambiguity no code reading can resolve
  ("is this behaviour intentional / the spec?"), call `ask_user` with a
  precise question. Use sparingly; for ordinary judgments decide and
  lower confidence if uncertain.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review the TESTS just added in {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Scope of the work (what the tests were meant to cover):
  target = {{vars.target}}
  requested types — unit:{{vars.test_unit}} integration:{{vars.test_integration}} e2e:{{vars.test_e2e}} other:{{vars.extra_test_kinds}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, immediately before —
  empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Tests/areas already audited earlier (both families — direct your
  coverage to fresh ground, do NOT shrink rigor):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE without new
  evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if every new test passes the mutation test
      and you audited them all (not a spot-check)
    - family: "claude"
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE TESTS only (façade / flaky /
      worthless — after self-critique)
    - fix_plan: concrete plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: test files / behaviours you actually audited this
      iteration (concise, e.g. "pkg/log/format_test.go — error paths +
      UTF-8 edges; mutation-checked"). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review the TESTS just added in {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Scope of the work:
  target = {{vars.target}}
  requested types — unit:{{vars.test_unit}} integration:{{vars.test_integration}} e2e:{{vars.test_e2e}} other:{{vars.extra_test_kinds}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  ## TOOL BUDGET — READ FIRST (tight — only 12 tool calls total).
  ## Anchor protocol — do EXACTLY this, then commit to a verdict. The
  ## tests are UNCOMMITTED in the working tree, so diff HEAD — NOT
  ## `HEAD^...HEAD` (that shows the base and loops review forever):
  ##   1. `bash: git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} diff HEAD --shortstat`
  ##   2. `bash: git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} diff HEAD --name-only`
  ##   3. Pick 2-3 new/changed TEST files. `read_file` each ONCE.
  ##   4. Optional: 1 targeted grep per concern, max 2-3.
  ##   5. Emit verdict.
  ## ~8 calls, under the 12 cap. Do NOT re-enumerate the diff with
  ## many greps — trust steps 1+2.

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, immediately before —
  empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Tests/areas already audited earlier:
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE without new
  evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if every new test passes the mutation test
      and you audited them all
    - family: "gpt"
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE TESTS only
    - fix_plan: concrete plan to fix the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: test files / behaviours you actually audited this
      iteration (concise). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt fix_system:
  You are an expert developer fixing blockers a reviewer raised on the
  TESTS added in this workflow run.

  WHY: the goal is tests that catch real regressions. When you fix a
  blocker, the fix must make the test MORE able to catch a bug — add
  the missing assertion, cover the skipped edge case, de-mock the unit
  under test, replace a frozen snapshot with a verified expectation,
  remove the flaky construct. NEVER fix a blocker by weakening a test
  or by editing the code under test to match a wrong expectation.

  SCOPE:
  1. Apply concrete edits to the TEST code to fix the reported
     blockers. Stay within the tests added this run; do NOT refactor
     unrelated code.
  2. After each fix, run the relevant tests with the repo's own runner
     to confirm they still pass (and still fail when they should —
     sanity-check at least one mutation if cheap). Keep
     `.test_coverage.verify.sh` accurate.

  PUSHBACK: you MAY refuse a blocker via `pushback` +
  `pushback_justification` when it is a style/naming nit, targets
  code outside the tests added this run, or contradicts the plan. Use
  sparingly — pushing back on everything wastes iterations.

  HUMAN ESCALATION: if a blocker is genuinely ambiguous (which
  behaviour is correct? is this the intended contract?), call
  `ask_user`. Not for technical decisions you can make alone.

  After applying fixes, STAGE everything: run
  `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A` so new files are visible to
  the next reviewer's `git diff HEAD`.

prompt fix_user:
  Apply concrete fixes to the blockers below, in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}. Stay within the tests added this run.

  Reported blockers:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Proposed fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker: if it is a real problem with a test (façade,
  flaky, missing assertion/edge), fix the TEST to make it stronger and
  re-run. If it is NOT a real blocker (style nit) or targets code
  outside the tests added this run, add it to `pushback` with a clear
  rationale in `pushback_justification`.

  After fixing, run `git -C {{vars.workspace_dir}} add -A`.

  Output:
    - applied: true if at least one fix was applied
    - summary: summary of fixes applied
    - pushback: refused items (empty if all fixed)
    - pushback_justification: rationale for the pushback

## ─── Prompts : Commit ────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt prepare_commit_system:
  Pick the EXACT set of files to commit to capture the tests added in
  this workflow run, and produce a semantic commit message. You do NOT
  run `git commit` — a deterministic shell tool downstream stages your
  file list and applies your message.

  This session forks from the implementation session, so the plan, the
  tests, and the simplification are in your history. Use that, plus a
  fresh `git status` / `git diff HEAD`, to decide.

  Procedure (in order):
    1. Run `git status` and `git diff HEAD` (read-only).
    2. Keep only the files that materialise the tests you added (test
       files; and product files ONLY if you made a genuine,
       reviewer-approved testability seam — note it).
    3. EXCLUDE anything not part of this test work: pre-existing WIP,
       build artifacts, coverage reports, the bot's own scratch
       (`.test_coverage.verify.sh`, `.test_coverage.verify.log`),
       editor/LLM scratch files. When in doubt, EXCLUDE.
    4. Build the structured output:
         - type = "test" (these are tests); scope, subject,
           full_message; files (exact repo-relative paths to stage);
           committed: false.

  Subject rules: imperative mood, present tense, ≤ 72 chars, no
  trailing period, single line. Prefer `test(<scope>): …`.

prompt prepare_commit_user:
  Pick the files and produce the semantic commit name for the tests
  you just added. Do not run `git commit` — only output the structured
  object.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

## ─── Schemas ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## verify_result is the DETERMINISTIC gate's contract. `passed` is the
## real process exit code of re-running .test_coverage.verify.sh — NOT
## an LLM judgment. `new_test_code` is true only when `git diff HEAD`
## (plus untracked files) shows genuinely-new test code added — the
## negative-space anti-façade check (the agent cannot just CLAIM it
## added tests; the diff must show it).
schema verify_result:
  passed: bool
  new_test_code: bool
  exit_code: int
  log_tail: string

schema repair_input:
  fail_log: string

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from ALL
  ## prior reviewer iterations (both families). Empty on iteration 1.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family enum-constrained so a hallucinated third value is rejected
  ## by structured-output validation instead of bypassing the fix
  ## routes and falling through to `done`.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  scanned_areas: string[]

## streak_check relays the verdict + computes a deterministic stop
## signal. Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection counts as approved
## for streak/fix routing (the reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a
## strong enough signal to trigger a fix cycle). cumulative_scanned_areas
## grows monotonically (outputs.streak_check resolves to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's value during this evaluation).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

schema commit_output:
  type: string [enum: "feat", "fix", "refactor", "test", "docs", "chore"]
  scope: string
  subject: string
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  committed: bool

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  workspace_dir: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## ─── Nodes : Plan → Act → Simplify ───────────────────────────────

agent plan:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bounded session — read-only exploration, a tighter cap is fine.
  tool_max_steps: 60
  system: plan_system
  user: plan_user
  session: fresh
  ## Persist the plan as a versioned artifact (studio Artifact tab +
  ## `iterion report`); `act` still inherits it via the session.
  publish: plan_artifact

agent act:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  ## Bound the agentic session (maps to claude --max-turns). Unbounded,
  ## a high-effort implementer accretes tool-result context until the
  ## CLI dies; error_max_turns is a graceful partial stop.
  tool_max_steps: 120
  system: act_system
  user: act_user
  session: inherit

agent simplify:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  tool_max_steps: 50
  user: simplify_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Nodes : Deterministic verify gate ───────────────────────────

## verify_run_tests is the FLOOR (no LLM). It re-runs the
## agent-prepared .test_coverage.verify.sh and reports the REAL exit
## code, AND checks `git diff HEAD` + untracked files for genuinely-new
## TEST code (universal test-naming conventions — NOT a language
## enumeration). No language or package manager appears here; it just
## executes whatever the adaptive act/repair agent wrote, so the gate
## stays universal while the verdict stays deterministic. python3 is
## used for safe JSON + subprocess capture; the body avoids double
## quotes (and avoids backslashes — uses [.] not \. and chr() for
## special chars) so it survives the .bot string + sh -c layers.
tool verify_run_tests:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} python3 -c "
import os, re, json, subprocess
ws = os.environ.get('WS', '.')

def git(args):
    try:
        p = subprocess.run(['git', '-C', ws] + args, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.STDOUT, text=True, timeout=120)
        return p.stdout or ''
    except Exception:
        return ''

# 1) Run the agent-written verify script (the real test suite).
script = os.path.join(ws, '.test_coverage.verify.sh')
if not os.path.exists(script):
    passed = False
    rc = 1
    out = 'no .test_coverage.verify.sh found; act/repair must write the build+test verify script (see the verify-tests skill)'
else:
    rc = 0
    out = ''
    try:
        p = subprocess.run(['sh', script], cwd=ws, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.STDOUT, text=True, timeout=1800)
        out = p.stdout or ''
        rc = p.returncode
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired as e:
        out = (e.output or '') + chr(10) + '[verify timed out after 1800s]'
        rc = 124
    except Exception as e:
        out = 'verify_run_tests could not execute the script: ' + str(e)
        rc = 1
    passed = rc == 0
    try:
        with open(os.path.join(ws, '.test_coverage.verify.log'), 'w', encoding='utf-8') as lf:
            lf.write(out)
    except OSError:
        pass

# 2) Negative-space anti-façade check: did real NEW test code land?
# Universal test-naming conventions (case-insensitive), no language enum.
rx = re.compile('(_test[.]|_tests[.]|[.]test[.]|[.]spec[.]|/test/|/tests/|/__tests__/|/spec/|(^|/)test_|_spec[.]|Test[.]|Tests[.]|Spec[.])', re.I)
added = 0
for line in git(['diff', 'HEAD', '--numstat']).splitlines():
    parts = line.split(chr(9))
    if len(parts) >= 3 and rx.search(parts[2]):
        try:
            added += int(parts[0])
        except ValueError:
            pass
untracked_test = False
for line in git(['status', '--porcelain']).splitlines():
    if line[:2].strip() == '??' and rx.search(line[3:]):
        untracked_test = True
        break
new_test_code = added > 0 or untracked_test

print(json.dumps({'passed': passed, 'new_test_code': new_test_code, 'exit_code': rc, 'log_tail': out[-4000:]}))
"`
  output: verify_result

agent repair_tests:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  tool_max_steps: 80
  input: repair_input
  output: verify_result
  system: repair_system
  user: repair_user
  session: inherit
  interaction: human

## ─── Nodes : Review / Fix Loop ───────────────────────────────────

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  ## Reviewer effort DECOUPLED from the implementer (defaults MEDIUM).
  ## A max-effort reviewer is pathologically thorough — it always
  ## re-raises some nit, so the "two consecutive cross-family
  ## approvals" gate never closes and the loop oscillates. Medium keeps
  ## it honest about REAL façade/worthless tests without false-positive
  ## churn. This is the convergence dial.
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW:-medium}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: openai/* models only work via claw. Without
  ## this the resolver routes through claude_code and the verdict fails
  ## schema validation.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_REVIEW:-medium}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names; without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  ## Tight cap forces a verdict instead of re-enumerating the diff via
  ## grep (the loop that hit context_length_exceeded on the forfait).
  tool_max_steps: 12
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector. stop=true iff current AND previous
## reviewers (opposite families) both APPROVED, high-confidence-gated:
## a rejection still counts as approval unless it carries confidence
## high. Only high-confidence façade/worthless-test blockers hold up
## the commit; medium/low concerns are recorded but don't gate (two
## reviewers almost always surface SOME nit each round, so gating on
## medium makes the double-approval statistically unreachable).
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "(input.approved || input.confidence != 'high') && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence != 'high'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each inherits the SAME-family reviewer's session
## (_session_id on the edge) so it reuses the prompt cache + loaded
## workspace + reasoning chain — one session per iteration per family.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  tool_max_steps: 80
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## ─── Nodes : Commit ──────────────────────────────────────────────

## prepare_commit forks the simplify session so it inherits the full
## context. Read-only: it runs git status / git diff HEAD, then emits a
## structured commit plan. It never stages or commits.
agent prepare_commit:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_VIBE_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_VIBE_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-high}"
  output: commit_output
  system: prepare_commit_system
  user: prepare_commit_user
  session: fork
  readonly: true

## commit_changes is a deterministic shell tool — no LLM. It stages the
## exact file list from prepare_commit and commits with the semantic
## message, EXCLUDING the bot's own verify scratch (committing it would
## pollute the target repo). add the listed files, reset the scratch,
## then commit only if something is staged.
tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -- {{input.files}} && { git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} reset -q -- .test_coverage.verify.sh .test_coverage.verify.log >/dev/null 2>&1 || true; git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}}; }"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## ─── Workflow ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow test_coverage:
  entry: plan

  ## Isolated git worktree at .iterion/worktrees/<run-id>/ — shields the
  ## user's main tree from mutations, makes prepare_commit structurally
  ## correct (no unrelated WIP to misclassify), and makes cleanup a
  ## one-line worktree remove.
  worktree: auto

  ## Container isolation on top of the worktree. The act/simplify/repair
  ## phases run the repo's build+test (go test / pnpm test / pytest / …)
  ## inferred from the project — the worktree alone doesn't sandbox
  ## those. Inline mode (not `mode: auto`) so we can pin the image AND
  ## install claude into it (the sandbox images don't ship the CLI; auto
  ## fallback drops post_create/mounts/env). Operators wanting a
  ## different toolchain edit this block — the single override point.
  sandbox:
    image: "ghcr.io/socialgouv/iterion-sandbox-full:edge"
    user: "1000:1000"
    mounts: ["type=bind,source=${localEnv:HOME}/.claude,target=/home/devbox/.claude,consistency=cached"]
    env:
      CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR: "/home/devbox/.claude"
    ## Gate on `claude --version` (runs the binary), NOT `command -v`
    ## (a broken/partial npm -g install exits 0 leaving a non-runnable
    ## binary). VERIFY after install + exit 1 on failure so a broken
    ## claude fails post_create (a clean sandbox-setup error the
    ## dispatcher retries) instead of failing cryptically mid-run.
    post_create: "set -e; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || sudo npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code@latest; claude --version >/dev/null 2>&1 || { echo 'claude install verification failed' >&2; exit 1; }"

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "4h"
    max_cost_usd: 120

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## ═══ Phase 1 : Plan → Act → Simplify ══════════════════════════
  ## One Claude Code session via session: inherit on act/simplify.
  plan -> act with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.plan._session_id}}"
  }
  act -> simplify with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.act._session_id}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 2 : Deterministic verify floor ═════════════════════
  ## The suite must pass AND real new test code must exist before the
  ## quality review begins. Red → repair (bounded) → re-run; the pass
  ## edge always wins when its condition is met (first-match-wins, so
  ## it is listed before the loop-bearing back edge + the fail
  ## fallthrough). Mirrors whole-improve-loop's verify_build/verify_run
  ## pair, placed as the floor.
  simplify -> verify_run_tests

  verify_run_tests -> alt when "passed && new_test_code"

  ## Not green (or no new tests) and the loop isn't exhausted → repair.
  ## repair_tests inherits simplify's session (resumed each iteration,
  ## so repairs chain) and receives the gate's real failure log.
  verify_run_tests -> repair_tests as verify_loop(3) with {
    fail_log: "{{outputs.verify_run_tests.log_tail}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.simplify._session_id}}"
  }
  repair_tests -> verify_run_tests

  ## verify_loop exhausted without green real tests → fail (no commit).
  ## Routed to fail (not done): a non-converging deterministic gate is
  ## not a silent success.
  verify_run_tests -> fail

  ## ═══ Phase 3 : Anti-façade review / fix loop ══════════════════
  ## Round-robin alternates claude / gpt. Each reviewer receives the
  ## OTHER family's most recent fixer pushback + the accumulated
  ## scanned areas. Empty on the first iteration.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed streak_check. The loop is attached here so the
  ## runtime snapshots the verdict as loop.review_loop.previous_output
  ## for the NEXT iteration.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.scanned_areas}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 4 : Commit on streak success ═══════════════════════
  ## Cross-family double-approval reached. prepare_commit (forked from
  ## simplify) emits the structured commit intent; commit_changes
  ## deterministically applies it.
  streak_check -> prepare_commit when stop with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.simplify._session_id}}"
  }
  prepare_commit -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.full_message}}",
    files: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.files}}",
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }
  commit_changes -> done

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR a non-high-confidence
  ## rejection treated as soft-approved): keep alternating without
  ## fixing. This edge does NOT carry review_loop (the counter
  ## increments once per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge).
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## High-confidence rejection WITH concrete blockers: route to the
  ## SAME-family fixer so it inherits the reviewer's session.
  ## _session_id reads directly from the most recent reviewer output
  ## (compute passthrough strips underscore-prefixed metadata). The
  ## length(blockers) > 0 guard avoids a wasted fixer round-trip on a
  ## coverage-only rejection with no concrete blocker.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Both fixers
  ## share the counter — total fix attempts capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> alt as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> alt as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop-exhaustion fallbacks → fail (NOT done): exhausting the loops
  ## without streak_check firing `stop` means no convergence + no
  ## commit; reporting `finished` there is a silent empty success. Legit
  ## success is streak_check (stop) → prepare_commit → commit_changes →
  ## done.
  reviewer_claude -> fail
  reviewer_gpt    -> fail
  fix_claude      -> fail
  fix_gpt         -> fail
  ## streak_check catch-all routes back to alt so an unmatched state
  ## keeps cycling rather than silently terminating; the bounded
  ## review_loop still guarantees exit via the reviewer→fail
  ## fallthrough.
  streak_check    -> alt
